{
  "texts": [
    "Given the nature of the task, researchers have been using the category of autoregressive large language transformer models designed for text generation to perform zero-shot classification (Gilardi et al., 2023; Ollion et al., 2023).",
    "Although autoencoding models mentioned previously (e.g., BERT) appear to be more appropriate for classification (Minaee et al., 2021), here we also assess the performance of GPT-3.5-turbo and GPT-4, two powerful autoregressive generative models.",
    "Unlike the autoencoding models for classification that calculate the probabilities of texts belonging to each coding category, generative models generate the coding category for each text when provided with a natural language instruction (i.e., a prompt).",
    "Autoregressive generative models can, in general, be instructed by providing them with (1) a larger number of manually coded examples (fine-tuning, as discussed with regard to autoencoding models), (2) a few representative examples (i.e., few-shot learning), or (3) only coding instructions in natural language (i.e., zero-shot learning) (Liu et al., 2021).",
    "Recent work has highlighted, in particular, the good performance of zero-shot classification on some tasks (Brown et al., 2020; Chae & Davidson, 2023), suggesting that this approach could support social scientific inquiry while reducing the costs and effort associated with fine-tuning of large language models (Rathje et al., 2023)."
  ]
}